\v 13 \bd \w not|strong="G3756"\w*\bd* \w like|strong="G2509"\w* \w Moses|strong="G3475"\w*, \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w put|strong="G5087"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w veil|strong="G2571"\w* \w over|strong="G1909"\w* \w his|strong="G1438"\w* \w own|strong="G1438"\w* \w face|strong="G4383"\w*, \w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w children|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w Israel|strong="G2474"\w* \w would|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* observe \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w end|strong="G5056"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w what|strong="G3588"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w fading|strong="G2673"\w*.\f + \fr 3:13 \ft At first he used the veil because the people found the shine to be disconcerting, but the shine faded, and he kept on using the veil so they couldn't see that it was gone. Any reflected light depends on the source, and constant exposure to that source.\f*
\v 14 \nd \w But|strong="G3361"\w*\nd*, \w it|strong="G3754"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w their|strong="G1722"\w* \w minds|strong="G3540"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* closed, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w to|strong="G1909"\w* \w this|strong="G3588"\w* \w day|strong="G2250"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w very|strong="G4594"\w* \w veil|strong="G2571"\w* \w remains|strong="G3306"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w place|strong="G1722"\w* \w when|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Old|strong="G3820"\w* \w Testament|strong="G1242"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* read, \w since|strong="G3754"\w* only \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w it|strong="G3754"\w* taken \w away|strong="G2673"\w*.
\v 15 Yes, \w even|strong="G2193"\w* \w to|strong="G1909"\w* \w this|strong="G3588"\w* \w day|strong="G4594"\w*, \w when|strong="G2259"\w* \w Moses|strong="G3475"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* read \w a|strong="G1909"\w* \w veil|strong="G2571"\w* \w lies|strong="G2749"\w* \w on|strong="G1909"\w* \w their|strong="G3588"\w* \w heart|strong="G2588"\w*.
\v 16 \w However|strong="G1161"\w*, \w whenever|strong="G1437"\w* \w anyone|strong="G1437"\w* \w turns|strong="G1994"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w veil|strong="G2571"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* removed.\f + \fr 3:16 \ft Any Jew can escape that veil—here is how.\f*
\v 17 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*,\f + \fr 3:17 \ft A clear statement that the Holy Spirit is God.\f* \w and|strong="G1161"\w* \w where|strong="G3757"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*'\w s|strong="G2962"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w there|strong="G1161"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w freedom|strong="G1657"\w*.\f + \fr 3:17 \ft “The Truth will make you free” (John 8:32). Several times the Lord Jesus referred to the Holy Spirit as the Spirit of \nd the\nd* Truth.\f*
\v 18 \w So|strong="G1161"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w*, contemplating \w as|strong="G1519"\w* \w in|strong="G1519"\w* \w a|strong="G1519"\w* \w mirror|strong="G2734"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w of|strong="G4151"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w with|strong="G1519"\w* unveiled \w face|strong="G4383"\w*,\f + \fr 3:18 \ft Comparing this text with others like Psalm 1:2-3, James 1:22-25, 2:12, Ephesians 6:17 and Hebrews 4:12, I conclude that the ‘mirror’ here refers to God's Word. As we spend time in the Word with “unveiled face” (sincerely open to what it says), the Holy Spirit moves us up from one plane of glory to another—the goal is “the same image”.\f* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w being|strong="G1161"\w* \w transformed|strong="G3339"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1519"\w* same \w image|strong="G1504"\w* \w from|strong="G3588"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w*, precisely \w from|strong="G3588"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w*.\f + \fr 3:18 \ft Had Paul been writing in Hebrew, I imagine we would have ‘Jehovah-Spirit’, or ‘Jehovah the Spirit’. He here reinforces what he already said in verse 17—the Holy Spirit is part of the Triune God.\f*
\c 4
\s1 But it isn't easy
\m 
\v 1 \w Therefore|strong="G1223"\w*, \w since|strong="G2192"\w* \w we|strong="G2192"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w received|strong="G1653"\w* \w mercy|strong="G1653"\w* along \w with|strong="G1223"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w ministry|strong="G1248"\w*, \w we|strong="G2192"\w* \w do|strong="G2192"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* lose heart.
\v 2 Rather, \w we|strong="G1722"\w* \w have|strong="G3956"\w* renounced \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w hidden|strong="G2927"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w* \w of|strong="G3056"\w* shame, \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w walking|strong="G4043"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* deception \w nor|strong="G3366"\w* falsifying \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Word|strong="G3056"\w* \w of|strong="G3056"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*,\f + \fr 4:2 \ft Alas, there is no lack of those who deceive and falsify.\f* \w but|strong="G3361"\w* \w by|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* open proclamation \w of|strong="G3056"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* Truth\f + \fr 4:2 \ft The importance of this is enlarged upon in 2 Thessalonians 2:10-12.\f* \w commending|strong="G4921"\w* \w ourselves|strong="G1438"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w every|strong="G3956"\w* \w man|strong="G3956"\w*'s \w conscience|strong="G4893"\w*, \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w sight|strong="G1799"\w* \w of|strong="G3056"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.
\v 3 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w where|strong="G1722"\w* \w our|strong="G2532"\w* \w Gospel|strong="G2098"\w* \w has|strong="G1510"\w* \w actually|strong="G2532"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* \w concealed|strong="G2572"\w*, \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w has|strong="G1510"\w* \w been|strong="G1510"\w* \w hidden|strong="G2572"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w being|strong="G1510"\w* wasted,
\v 4 \w among|strong="G1722"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w god|strong="G2316"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* age \w has|strong="G2316"\w* \w blinded|strong="G5186"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w minds|strong="G3540"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* unbelieving,\f + \fr 4:4 \ft The Text clearly states that Satan, “the god of this age”, is in the business of blinding the minds of unbelievers when they hear the Gospel, so they will not understand, so they will not be convicted, so they will not repent and convert. This is a terrible truth, the most terrible truth in the world, at least as I see it. The enemy has access to our minds, access in the sense that he has the power or ability to invade them, whether by introducing thoughts or by jamming our reasoning. The Lord Jesus had already declared this truth previously, when He explained the parable of the sower. “These are the ones by the wayside where the word is sown; but, as soon as they hear it Satan comes and takes away the word that was planted in their hearts” (Mark 4:15). In the parallel passage in Luke 8:12 Jesus adds the following words: “lest they believe and be saved.” Note that the Word is already in the mind or heart of the person, but then Satan comes, invades the mind and “takes away” that word. I am not sure just how this intrusion by the enemy works, perhaps he causes a mental block of some sort, but the practical effect is that the Word becomes ineffective, as if the person had not even heard it.\fp The crucial question then becomes, what can we do about it? We find the answer in Mark 3:27. “No one can plunder the strong man's goods, invading his house, unless he first bind the strong man; then he may plunder his house.” I have used the definite article with the first occurrence of ‘strong man’ because the Greek Text has it, the point being that this particular strong man has already been introduced in the immediate context. “The strong man” here is Satan. (The Jewish leaders tried to explain Jesus' authority over the demons by saying that He expelled them by the power of Beelzebul, prince of the demons. In His retort Jesus does not waste time with that name but uses the enemy's proper name, Satan.)\fp So then, the Lord Jesus declares that it is impossible to steal Satan's goods unless we bind him first. (From His use of “no one” it seems clear that the Lord is enunciating a general principle or truth.) And what might the nature of those ‘goods’ be? In the context (see Matthew 12:22-24) Jesus had delivered someone from a demon that caused blindness and dumbness, and in their comments the scribes and Pharisees include other instances where Jesus had expelled demons—it seems clear that the “goods” are people who are subject to Satan's power, in one way or another. Thus we have the same essential truth as that declared in Acts 26:18—we have to do something about Satan's power over a person so that he or she can be saved! So what can we do? Since the point of handcuffs is to keep someone from acting, I believe that in so many words, aloud or in thought, we must forbid Satan from interfering in the minds of our hearers, before we preach. For more on this subject the reader may consult my site: \nd www.prunch.org\nd*.\f* \w so|strong="G1519"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w light|strong="G5462"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Gospel|strong="G2098"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*, \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w image|strong="G1504"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*, \w should|strong="G2316"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* dawn \w on|strong="G1722"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*.
\p 
\v 5 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w we|strong="G1063"\w* \w do|strong="G1223"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w proclaim|strong="G2784"\w* \w ourselves|strong="G1438"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w as|strong="G1161"\w* Sovereign,\f + \fr 4:5 \ft That is what the Text says; Christ Jesus must be proclaimed as Lord/Sovereign, nothing less.\f* \w and|strong="G1161"\w* \w ourselves|strong="G1438"\w* \w as|strong="G1161"\w* \w your|strong="G1223"\w* \w servants|strong="G1401"\w*\f + \fr 4:5 \ft Literally, ‘slaves’.\f* \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*' \w sake|strong="G1223"\w*;
\v 6 \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* commanded \w light|strong="G5457"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w shine|strong="G2989"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w darkness|strong="G4655"\w*\f + \fr 4:6 \ft See Genesis 1:3.\f* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w He|strong="G3739"\w* \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w shined|strong="G2989"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w hearts|strong="G2588"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w give|strong="G3004"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w light|strong="G5457"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* comes \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w knowledge|strong="G1108"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w glory|strong="G1391"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w face|strong="G4383"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G3004"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*.\f + \fr 4:6 \ft Did you get that? When you really look at Jesus you see God's glory; that knowledge becomes a light shining in your heart. Wonderful!\f*
\v 7 Further, \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w treasure|strong="G2344"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w jars|strong="G4632"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w clay|strong="G3749"\w*,\f + \fr 4:7 \ft That we are clay pots does not change the nature of the “treasure”.\f* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* all-surpassing \w power|strong="G1411"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w ourselves|strong="G2249"\w*\f + \fr 4:7 \ft God gives us the privilege of using His power, but we had better not try to take the credit!\f*
\v 8 —\w we|strong="G1722"\w* \w are|strong="G3956"\w* hard-pressed \w on|strong="G1722"\w* \w every|strong="G3956"\w* \w side|strong="G3956"\w*, yet \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w crushed|strong="G4729"\w*; perplexed, but \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w despair|strong="G1820"\w*;
\v 9 \w persecuted|strong="G1377"\w*, yet \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w abandoned|strong="G1459"\w*; knocked \w down|strong="G2598"\w*, but \w not|strong="G3756"\w* out;\f + \fr 4:9 \ft Dear me, this really doesn't sound like ‘easy street’ or a ‘bed of roses’! Paul is talking about very real struggle.\f*
\v 10 \w always|strong="G3842"\w* \w carrying|strong="G4064"\w* \w about|strong="G1722"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w body|strong="G4983"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w putting|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* death \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Lord|strong="G3588"\w*\f + \fr 4:10 \ft Perhaps 5% of the Greek manuscripts omit “Lord”, to be followed by NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.\f* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w life|strong="G2222"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* \w manifested|strong="G5319"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w our|strong="G2424"\w* \w body|strong="G4983"\w*.\f + \fr 4:10 \ft One is reminded of 1 Corinthians 15:31, where Paul says, “I die daily”. Clearly he cannot be referring to physical death, so it must be a dying to self. As I die to myself, to my own ideas and desires, the life of Jesus will be manifested in and through me. Or as he put it in Galatians 2:20, “I have been crucified with Christ, so it is no longer I who live but Christ lives in me; what I now live in this body I live by faith in the Son of God, who loved me and gave Himself in my place.”\f*
\v 11 \w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w*, \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w living|strong="G2198"\w*, \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w always|strong="G1223"\w* \w being|strong="G2532"\w* \w handed|strong="G3860"\w* \w over|strong="G3860"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w death|strong="G2288"\w* \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*' \w sake|strong="G1223"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w life|strong="G2222"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* \w manifested|strong="G5319"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w our|strong="G2424"\w* \w mortal|strong="G2349"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w*.\f + \fr 4:11 \ft You can't have resurrection without death.\f*
\v 12 \w So|strong="G1161"\w* \w then|strong="G1161"\w*, \w death|strong="G2288"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w at|strong="G1722"\w* \w work|strong="G1754"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w us|strong="G2249"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w life|strong="G2222"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*.\f + \fr 4:12 \ft There are stages in Christian life and ministry: at their beginning stage, Paul is paying the price for them to have life; later, they should pay the price for others to have life; and so on.\f*
\s1 Momentary affliction; eternal glory
\p 
\v 13 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w since|strong="G2192"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w same|strong="G2532"\w* \w spirit|strong="G4151"\w* \w of|strong="G4151"\w* \w faith|strong="G4102"\w*, \w just|strong="G2532"\w* \w like|strong="G2596"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w written|strong="G1125"\w*, “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w believed|strong="G4100"\w*; \w therefore|strong="G1352"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w spoke|strong="G2980"\w*,”\f + \fr 4:13 \ft See Psalm 116:10. We speak on the basis of what we believe.\f* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w believe|strong="G4100"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w therefore|strong="G1352"\w* \w speak|strong="G2980"\w*,
\v 14 \w knowing|strong="G1492"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w raised|strong="G1453"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w raise|strong="G1453"\w* \w us|strong="G2249"\w* \w through|strong="G5210"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*\f + \fr 4:14 \ft Our resurrection depends upon that of Jesus.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w present|strong="G3936"\w* \w us|strong="G2249"\w* \w together|strong="G4862"\w* \w with|strong="G4862"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*.
