\v 4 \w because|strong="G1063"\w* \w the|strong="G4314"\w* \w weapons|strong="G3696"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w warfare|strong="G4752"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* physical, \w but|strong="G1063"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w powerful|strong="G1415"\w* \w in|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w for|strong="G1063"\w* demolishing \w strongholds|strong="G3794"\w*:\f + \fr 10:4 \ft The subject of biblical spiritual warfare is generally not well understood in Christian circles. Much of what has been written concerns defensive procedures, but this text speaks of demolishing strongholds (presumably the enemy's, since no one will want to destroy his own), that has to do with taking the offensive. For more on this subject the reader may consult my site: \nd www.prunch.org\nd*.\f*
\v 5 demolishing sophistries\f + \fr 10:5 \ft A sophistry is a false argument that is presented in such a way as to appear correct, and impressive, especially if not properly analyzed. Satan has purveyed a number of sophistries designed to keep people from the knowledge of God, such as humanism, relativism, materialism, Freudianism, and so on.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w every|strong="G3956"\w* arrogance \w that|strong="G3588"\w* sets \w itself|strong="G1869"\w* \w up|strong="G1869"\w* \w against|strong="G2596"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w knowledge|strong="G1108"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*; taking captive \w every|strong="G3956"\w* \w thought|strong="G3540"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w make|strong="G1519"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w obedient|strong="G5218"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*;
\v 6 \w being|strong="G2532"\w* \w ready|strong="G2092"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w punish|strong="G1556"\w* \w every|strong="G3956"\w* act \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w disobedience|strong="G3876"\w*, \w whenever|strong="G3752"\w* \w your|strong="G2192"\w* \w obedience|strong="G5218"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w complete|strong="G4137"\w*.\f + \fr 10:6 \ft I suppose that the three gerunds—‘demolishing sophistries’, ‘taking captive every thought’ and ‘being ready to punish’—are some of our weapons, being grammatically subordinated to ‘demolishing strongholds’. In the context, the thoughts we take captive are not our own (though that also is a good thing to do), but those of the enemy's servants. I do this in so many words, aloud or in thought, and thereby avoid unnecessary complications.\f*
\s1 Paul is criticized
\p 
